	It doesn't matter what kind of service a host supports (Mark claims
	that 3Com.COM is okay since it's only got MX service, "like, no one is
	going to go FTP'ing or anything" ... like, Mark, it's just a tag --
	just a label.  All "domain names" are potential "hostnames" ... don't
	go special-case-ing on us ...

Not true.  3comvax.3Com.COM might be a potential host name, (if 3Com were
still in the TCP/IP business, which they aren't) but 3Com.COM is not a
host name, it's a parent domain name.

An interesting related question is whether the name olds@3Com.COM is
an allowed domain name even if 3Com.COM isn't a valid host name.  The
way the mail system is set up, on the Internet, mail to a domain like
3Com.COM can be MX'ed to 3comvax.3Com.COM so nobody actually opens a
connection to a "host" 3Com.COM, indeed there needn't be any such host.
Much like Mark.Horton@ATT.COM, there is no ATT.COM host, although there
are 5 mail gateways into ATT.COM.  (There is no COM host, either.)

I claim there is no reason for any host to ever try to open a
connection to 3Com.COM, even if they were to eventually join the
Internet.  There would never be a host called 3Com.COM.  Their
hosts would all be something.3Com.COM, and even if they accept
mail to user@3Com.COM, the MX system would direct it to a particular
host.

Is there anything wrong with this claim?

	Mark

